Pax, id est nomen mihi. Pax is ‘particula silentium imponentis? as Ter. Haut. 717 unus est dies, dum argentum eripio: pax: nil amplius, ‘say no more‚’ ‘ enough,’ ‘ basta,' and so Mil. 808 Pax, abi, ‘basta, off with you.' The interjection is Greek, and is explained by Hesychius πάξετέλος ἔχει. As Leo says it is ‘aptum nomen quod in utraque lingua abrumpendo sermoni adhibeatur) The name seems to be in- tended to shew that its owner will not stop to argue or listen to reason, and so Charmides calls it ‘a swindling name.’ Perhaps we may translate ‘Basta,'—‘ that is my name.’ N iemeyer gives Prax from Pseud. 1279.
